The paper deals with algorithms for computing treewidth, which is a fundamental graph parameter studied in computer science. The use of dynamic programming is a common technique for computing treewidth, and the paper builds on previous work in this area. The paper also discusses an iterative improvement procedure for treewidth upper bounds, which is a common approach in the literature. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The paper also discusses the use of heuristics and experiments to evaluate the performance of the algorithm, which suggests that it could be relevant to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
